								</div>
								<p>1. Tea: The base of any boba tea is typically black or green tea. Some variations use oolong, white, or herbal teas. The type of tea used can significantly influence the flavor of the drink.</p>
								<p>2. Milk: Traditional boba tea includes milk or a non-dairy alternative like almond, soy, or oat milk. The milk adds a creamy texture and balances the bitterness of the tea.</p>
								<p>3. Sweetener: Boba tea is often sweetened with sugar, honey, or flavored syrups. The sweetness level can usually be adjusted according to personal preference.</p>
								<p>4. Tapioca Pearls: Also known as boba, these chewy balls are made from tapioca starch and are the defining feature of boba tea. They are usually boiled until soft and then soaked in a sugary syrup for added flavor.</p>
